stylometry: Transshipment problems are more complex than transportation problems because they can involve warehouses where goods can be shipped to and from as a passing point as a cost effective option as opposed to only shipping from producer to consumer (or manufacturer to place of retail) like a trnasportation problem. For example with transshipment there can be a flow from manufacturer of auto frames in Mexico to a warehouse in the US to an auto-assembly company in Canada (as opposed to with transportation direct from Mexico to Canada). Say for example, in expanse of this problem, there are two warehouses in the US, one in Texas and one in North Dakota. The nodes would be all of these locations (Mexico, North Dakota, Texas, and Canada).  The arcs are the pathes the goods take to reach their destination a) Mexico, Texas, Canada b) Mexico, Canada c) Mexico, North Dakota, Canada d) Mexico, Texas, North Dakota, Canada etc. The flows would be the amount of goods traveling through each arc of nodes. The final result for the arcs are flows are determined by which is most effective (cost, or otherwise) through optimization.
